Harassment intended in a joking manner still constitutes unacceptable behavior. Between Ecological System Prediction and Environmental Security","code":null,"start":"2021-11-06T05:00:00.000Z","end":"2021-11-11T04:00:00.000Z","description":"According to Clark et al. (2001), ecological forecasting is the process of predicting the state of ecosystems, ecosystem services, and natural capital, with fully specified uncertainties, and is contingent on explicit scenarios for climate, land use, human population, technologies, and economic activity. Environmental security can be defined as the security impacts of weather, water, and climate directly on people (i.e., human security) and on overall societies (i.e., national security). (American Meteorological Society, 2021). Both areas share common characteristics: 1) both have spatial and temporal aspects; 2) both must consider the interaction between natural environmental events and humans living in it, to include the need for humans to react to, mitigate, or adapt to the changes brought about by either natural or anthropogenically driven events; 3) the environment may only be one of several \"drivers\" to changes in the system; 4) both must consider socio-economic and other factors besides the natural environment, which makes the problem hard to specify, bound, and predict.  The AMS Committees on Environmental Security and Ecological Forecasting are starting a dialogue to examine the potential connections and synergies between their respective approaches for evaluating the effects and impacts of natural and human-induced perturbations to their respective systems (ecological and national/human security). The purpose of this presentation is to introduce environmental security to this audience with the intent opening a dialogue on ways in which our respective areas (ecological forecasting, environmental security) could be extended into the study of potential impacts to marine interests resulting from these same natural environmental events and human activities, and developing methods to assess system status, magnitude of perturbations to the system, and the resulting economic, social, and security implications.","enrolled":false,"featured":false,"openForRegistration":true,"openForAttendeeHub@appFeature({\"feature\":\"displayInAttendeeHub\"})":null,"virtual":false,"included":false,"category":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionCategory:9c44cb55-29fe-41c9-8e87-8ee20bc6768f","typename":"SessionCategory"},"location":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionLocation:07bcd0d6-ded7-4edc-849a-9c6f0fd2de46","typename":"SessionLocation"},"webcast":null,"exhibitors":null,"__typename":"Session"},"SessionLocation:07bcd0d6-ded7-4edc-849a-9c6f0fd2de46":{"id":"07bcd0d6-ded7-4edc-849a-9c6f0fd2de46","name":"VIRTUAL","code":"VIRTUAL","__typename":"SessionLocation"},"Session:5e137326-400b-4d87-adaa-631ca2485253":{"id":"5e137326-400b-4d87-adaa-631ca2485253","name":"A climate-driven shifting portfolio of Wisconsin recreational fishing opportunities, and how we d","code":null,"start":"2021-11-06T05:00:00.000Z","end":"2021-11-11T04:00:00.000Z","description":"emonstrate and discuss it using CAP trainingClimate change is currently one of the primary forces structuring recreational fisheries dynamics in inland lakes, and is projected to become even more pronounced. Fisheries management agencies must adaptively manage fisheries to react to this change while maximizing fishery benefits for stakeholders, and doing this successfully necessitates clear communication about climate and fisheries science with policymakers, anglers, and other stakeholders. In Wisconsin, where climate change is contributing to walleye declines, cisco and lake whitefish extirpations, expansions of bass and bluegill fisheries, threatened trout streams becoming more reliant on fluctuating groundwater inputs, and a suite of other changes, the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources and university partners have assembled relevant climate information on fisheries and many other issues as part of the Wisconsin Initiative on Climate Change Impacts (WICCI). As a member of the WICCI Fisheries Working Group, I have applied by Climate Ambassador Program (CAP) training to my own research and a statewide public-facing WICCI report. In this talk, I will summarize this report and highlight recent research into how climate projections translate into a shifting and potentially dwindling portfolio of lake types and fishing opportunities, and what this means for anglers and fisheries management. I will share narratives, data metrics, and visualizations workshopped during CAP training that summarize this research for public audiences.","enrolled":false,"featured":false,"openForRegistration":true,"openForAttendeeHub@appFeature({\"feature\":\"displayInAttendeeHub\"})":null,"virtual":false,"included":false,"category":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionCategory:73ff5b99-b8de-4339-9c94-a7b94a067e35","typename":"SessionCategory"},"location":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionLocation:07bcd0d6-ded7-4edc-849a-9c6f0fd2de46","typename":"SessionLocation"},"webcast":null,"exhibitors":null,"__typename":"Session"},"Session:09bb7b34-4333-44f6-a237-cde4c0391bea":{"id":"09bb7b34-4333-44f6-a237-cde4c0391bea","name":"A Community of Practice to Advance Management of Introduced Aquatic Species","code":null,"start":"2021-11-06T05:00:00.000Z","end":"2021-11-11T04:00:00.000Z","description":"Genevieve Johnson Bureau of ReclamationLarry Fisher University of ArizonaKrystie Miner University of ArizonaAnna Weinberg University of ArizonaJessica Gwinn U.S. Fish and Wildlife ServiceAlex Koeberle Cornell UniversityFALSEThe U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and Bureau of Reclamation work together to support coordination among federal and state agencies, conservation organizations, universities and research centers, and local governments in the Southwest. Introduced aquatic species are a primary management challenge for aquatic ecosystems. These invertebrates, amphibians, fish, and other introduced species are seen by many as the primary impediment to conservation or recovery of native aquatic species, especially in a warming, drying climate. In 2020, the Collaborative Conservation and Adaptation Strategy Toolbox (CCAST) team launched the Southwest Non-Native Aquatic Species Community of Practice to increase communication and coordination to address this challenge. The team worked with an initial group of 28 members to develop Year 1 objectives. Objectives included communication of success stories, development of decision-support tools, and establishment of mechanisms to co-develop actionable science. Key accomplishments as of April 2021 include completion of 17 related case studies on CCAST, 13 webinars, and development of a project catalog for both new and experienced practitioners to learn how others are setting goals for and implementing control projects. In early 2021, the team hosted two workshop series, one on American bullfrogs and one on Green Sunfish, to discuss impacts on native species, best practices for control projects and programs, and opportunities for increased coordination. The team also hosted three research priority discussions, resulting in over $700,000 being committed to research on American bullfrogs and introduced crayfish in Arizona and New Mexico. Moving forward, the Community of Practice will finish a suite of decision-support tools and build on actionable workshop outcomes. The team will continue fostering communication for a growing membership, currently with over 125 individuals from a geography expanding across the West and beyond.","enrolled":false,"featured":false,"openForRegistration":true,"openForAttendeeHub@appFeature({\"feature\":\"displayInAttendeeHub\"})":null,"virtual":false,"included":false,"category":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionCategory:303ced98-8726-4db5-84c9-f2ba0175e276","typename":"SessionCategory"},"location":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionLocation:07bcd0d6-ded7-4edc-849a-9c6f0fd2de46","typename":"SessionLocation"},"webcast":null,"exhibitors":null,"__typename":"Session"},"Session:6c113dce-086a-4001-9934-6d98e45831ee":{"id":"6c113dce-086a-4001-9934-6d98e45831ee","name":"A Governance Network Approach to Offshore Wind  Fisheries Conflict in Southern New England","code":null,"start":"2021-11-06T05:00:00.000Z","end":"2021-11-11T04:00:00.000Z","description":"Offshore wind development stands on the brink of rapid expansion in the United States. With two small projects to date, including the 30-MW Block Island Wind Farm, there are 16 lease areas encompassing over 1.7 million acres in U.S. waters, and numerous additional areas designated for future development. While advocates tout offshore wind as critical to climate change mitigation, reaction from ocean users is mixed, with commercial fishers representing the most vocal group opposing these developments. This opposition led to multi-year delays in permitting for the 800-MW Vineyard Wind project, which is poised to be the first large-scale development in federal waters. This suggests that marine renewable energy is a major source of concern in fishing-dependent communities, and that fisheries-related conflict may represent a significant barrier to advancing the growth of marine renewable energy in the U.S. How does the southern New England offshore wind governance network shape fisheries conflict, and to what extent does it provide opportunities for cooperation? This research used a governance network approach to analyze interactions between commercial fishers, fisheries advocates, government agencies, and others involved in southern New England offshore wind decision-making. This study employed thematic analysis and social network analysis in order to characterize the network in which these stakeholders and agencies work; analyze the role and influence of, and interactions between, these actors; and examine the extent to which network characteristics facilitated conflict or cooperation. This presentation will highlight key findings and identify policy lessons learned and areas for future research.","enrolled":false,"featured":false,"openForRegistration":true,"openForAttendeeHub@appFeature({\"feature\":\"displayInAttendeeHub\"})":null,"virtual":false,"included":false,"category":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionCategory:36803e87-2b6a-4e1e-92a6-823aaf63f860","typename":"SessionCategory"},"location":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionLocation:07bcd0d6-ded7-4edc-849a-9c6f0fd2de46","typename":"SessionLocation"},"webcast":null,"exhibitors":null,"__typename":"Session"},"Session:70530825-17f1-4093-8753-7185008bf6b6":{"id":"70530825-17f1-4093-8753-7185008bf6b6","name":"A Historical Perspective on Thermal Effects Research, Applications, and Regulation Through Five D","code":null,"start":"2021-11-06T05:00:00.000Z","end":"2021-11-11T04:00:00.000Z","description":"ecadesBefore 1970 thermal effects was limited to academic research that produced the foundational concepts of thermal biology. The understanding and regulation of thermal effects was in its infancy. Section 316(a) of the 1972 Clean Water Act was the impetus for unprecedented thermal effects research - hundreds of laboratory and field studies were produced in the 1970s. This was applied to the regulation of existing thermal discharges from the generation of electricity. The focus was on maximum temperatures that would maintain and protect a balanced indigenous population of fish, shellfish, and aquatic life and under critical flow and ambient temperature. The research that was available at that time produced physiological and behavioral endpoints for fish which were assumed to be the most sensitive component of a balanced indigenous population. The upper incipient lethal temperature, the critical thermal maximum, and optima for growth and reproduction were physiological endpoints. Behavioral endpoints included upper avoidance and final preferred temperatures. These were used to execute demonstrations of a lack of prior appreciable harm from thermal discharges and the prediction of the same for new discharges. Field studies used to assess the effects of thermal discharges prompted the development of field-based endpoints similar to behavioral endpoints. States adopted temperature criteria based on recommendations of federal agency expert panels that resulted in seasonal or monthly maximum temperatures suitable for protection and propagation of warm water and cold water fish. With 50 years of hindsight, gaps in the science of that time is readily apparent, yet today most temperature standards have not been modernized. A database that we have maintained since 1980 is still predominated by lethal endpoints. Newer and non-lethal endpoints are sparse in the database. It remains to be seen how well this can support the assessment and prediction of temperature impairments.","enrolled":false,"featured":false,"openForRegistration":true,"openForAttendeeHub@appFeature({\"feature\":\"displayInAttendeeHub\"})":null,"virtual":false,"included":false,"category":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionCategory:18e76aed-323b-4476-beff-0f1dd2e392ea","typename":"SessionCategory"},"location":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionLocation:07bcd0d6-ded7-4edc-849a-9c6f0fd2de46","typename":"SessionLocation"},"webcast":null,"exhibitors":null,"__typename":"Session"},"Session:2c16200d-bcc1-4101-b996-cbf3ba76be62":{"id":"2c16200d-bcc1-4101-b996-cbf3ba76be62","name":"A History of the Management of Common Carp Introductions","code":null,"start":"2021-11-06T05:00:00.000Z","end":"2021-11-11T04:00:00.000Z","description":"Common Carp (Cyprus carpio) are among the most widespread and most problematic invasive fishes in North America. The Gulf of Maine Distinct Population Segment of Atlantic Salmon has been listed as endangered by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and National Marine Fisheries Service.  Diminished habitat quality and accessibility are among the leading threats to the population. As with other salmonids, Atlantic salmon need access to cold-water refugia throughout the warmest parts of the summer, particularly in the southern portions of their range.  Baseflow is especially important habitat for Atlantic salmon and other aquatic species because of its influence on water quantity and river temperatures during the summer low-flow period. The identification of areas that have relatively high amounts of baseflow during the low-flow season is a first step in assessing factors that affect river temperature and the relative abundance of habitat for aquatic species.  We present a regression model that we have applied to ungaged streams throughout Maine to help resource managers assess relative amounts of baseflow in streams with Maine Atlantic Salmon habitat. We derived the model from August mean baseflows computed at 31 USGS streamgages in and near the Gulf of Maine. An ordinary least squares regression model estimates August mean baseflow per unit drainage area using two explanatory variables: percentage of the basin underlain by sand and gravel aquifers, and the basin mean July precipitation. This model provides the means to estimate August mean baseflow in cubic feet per second per square mile of basin area on user-selected ungaged sites throughout Maine south of 46 2155 N latitude. Since the early 1900s, within- and among-species diversity has been reduced, extant populations have become isolated, and some forms have become extinct.  Successful coregonine restoration could increase prey fish diversity, reconnect ecologically important energy pathways, increase ecosystem resilience, and contribute to the sustainability of economically important fisheries.  Recently, a bi-national council of fishery management agency representatives endorsed an adaptive, basin-wide framework to restore coregonines in the Great Lakes.  Applied at the lake level, fishery management agencies 1) cooperatively define restoration priorities, 2) use science to inform restoration planning, 3) implement prioritized and integrated restoration plans, 4) evaluate and report on the restoration response, 5) redefine priorities, if necessary.  Multiagency teams of experts are developing consensus methodologies to inform the science planning in four key areas: resolving taxonomy and identifying restoration units, identifying key losses in habitats and populations, assessing threats, and conducting population viability analyses.  In some regions, where species are extirpated, fishery managers have already initiated restoration plans.  In summary, the coregonine restoration framework offers a cooperative pathway to undertake a science-based approach to address a high-priority and complex fishery management issue.","enrolled":false,"featured":false,"openForRegistration":true,"openForAttendeeHub@appFeature({\"feature\":\"displayInAttendeeHub\"})":null,"virtual":false,"included":false,"category":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionCategory:d25cdba9-bdb7-429c-b483-13609de42cb7","typename":"SessionCategory"},"location":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionLocation:07bcd0d6-ded7-4edc-849a-9c6f0fd2de46","typename":"SessionLocation"},"webcast":null,"exhibitors":null,"__typename":"Session"},"Session:7be30d6f-284c-4adf-8ddf-17d4ba5aba25":{"id":"7be30d6f-284c-4adf-8ddf-17d4ba5aba25","name":"A Profile of Atlantic Artificial Reef Development and Sport Fish Restoration Program Contributions","code":null,"start":"2021-11-06T05:00:00.000Z","end":"2021-11-11T04:00:00.000Z","description":"Keith Mille Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation CommissionFALSEMarine artificial reef development has long been a cornerstone of creating new recreational fishing and boating opportunities for sport fish anglers. When properly constructed and strategically sited, artificial reefs can enhance fish habitat, increase access to quality fishing grounds, benefit fishers and the economies of coastal communities, increase total fish biomass within a given area, and provide managers with another option for the conservation and management of fishery resources. The Atlantic States Marine Fisheries Commissions (Commission) Artificial Reef Committee (Committee) was established in 1986, soon after the inception of the Sport Fish Restoration Program (1984) and the release of the National Artificial Reef Plan (1985). The goal of the Committee is to coordinate artificial reef development activities in the Atlantic Ocean within both state and federal waters. The Committee evaluates current artificial reef issues, provides guidance on those issues, and shares best practices, lessons learned, and successes among state coordinators, Commissioners, and stakeholders. In 1988, the Commission published A Profile of Atlantic Artificial Reef Development, which featured profiles for each states artificial reef program. In the 30+ years since its release, many states have expanded their programs; deployed a variety of artificial reefs at over 300 sites using best management practices for construction, materials, and siting; and have monitored sites for use  both by fishers and divers, as well as by marine life. In July 2021, the Committee published an update to the 1988 publication, available here: ASMFC_Profiles_StateArtificialReefPrograms_Projects_July2021.pdf. Since then, there have been numerous changes to regulations and management measures through either fishery management plan amendments or regulatory amendments, in response to stock assessment results, modifications in stock status, and changes in the fishery. Recently, NOAA Fisheries has observed a decline in the commercial Atlantic shark fishery and changes in the recreational fishery. In the commercial fishery, trends include a reduction in landings, a decrease in active vessels, and an increase in shark discards. In the recreational fishery, trends include an increase in catch and release rates, an increase in effort by state-water or shore-based fishermen, and a decrease in targeted pelagic shark trips. To determine the root causes of many of these issues and trends, NOAA Fisheries reviewed the current state of the shark fishery, including examination of commercial shark fishery vessel permits, commercial trips targeting or retaining sharks, commercial shark landings, commercial dealer permits, market pricing and revenues, recreational shark endorsement permits, recreational fishing effort, recreational survey data, and tournament landings. Punt University of Washington, School of Aquatic and Fishery SciencesFALSEOno et al. 2017 implemented a species interaction model for the groundfish fishery in the Bering Sea and Aleutian Islands (BSAI) as part of a mixed species Management Strategy Evaluation (MSE) to incorporate technical interactions between target and bycatch species. The MSE integrated population dynamics and management system constraints related to technical interactions to account for differences in Acceptable Biological Catch (ABC), Total Allowable Catch (TAC), and realized catch across a group of fishery mtiers. These mtiers were determined using a static k-means cluster analysis across both space and time. Due to the anticipated environmental changes expected in the Bering Sea ecosystem, an improved understanding of the spatio-temporal dynamics of species catch composition will be critical in the implementation of future mixed species MSEs.We present results from a spatio-temporal cluster analysis of groundfish catch compositions for the BSAI. Models were implemented using a new R package, clustTMB. This package improves the cluster analysis for the BSAI multispecies fishery by incorporating statistical distributions more appropriate to fishery biomass data, including covariates in cluster membership probability, and incorporating spatio-temporal random effects. We built a model to determine the likelihood that each of 776 dams, culverts and waterfalls in New Jersey act as barriers to each of thirteen fish species during migration.  We assessed each fish species at each potential barrier to determine if the fish could jump high enough to clear the barrier, swim fast enough to overcome the velocity of water to reach the barrier, dive deep enough in the plunge pool to reach maximum jump height, and persist with migration given predicted water temperatures.  If all four were possible, the potential barrier was deemed passable.  Blockages were mostly the result of predicted weak jumping abilities and water temperatures outside the acceptable range during migration.  The model successfully predicted presence and absence above potential barriers for all species except the ubiquitous white sucker (Catostomus commersonii).  All locations with possible barriers were predicted to block at least two migratory fish species; 89% were predicted to block all species.  Alewife (Alosa pseudoharengus) and  blueback herring (Alosa aestivalis) were predicted to be blocked the most.  Results allow prediction of which potential barriers block passage for each species, the length of waterways blocked by each barrier, and the reasons each barrier is predicted to block each species.  We present our fish passage model as a tool for identifying possible barriers which if restored or removed, given appropriate field assessment, might reconnect migratory fish species with additional spawning habitat.","enrolled":false,"featured":false,"openForRegistration":true,"openForAttendeeHub@appFeature({\"feature\":\"displayInAttendeeHub\"})":null,"virtual":false,"included":false,"category":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionCategory:566f0fdc-e6b8-4a50-8f12-5a1e2272e8fb","typename":"SessionCategory"},"location":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionLocation:07bcd0d6-ded7-4edc-849a-9c6f0fd2de46","typename":"SessionLocation"},"webcast":null,"exhibitors":null,"__typename":"Session"},"Session:8966d7e6-e922-474d-9b3a-70bf735e73ca":{"id":"8966d7e6-e922-474d-9b3a-70bf735e73ca","name":"A state-space length-based assessment model for Korea chub mackerel","code":null,"start":"2021-11-06T05:00:00.000Z","end":"2021-11-11T04:00:00.000Z","description":"Doyul Kim Korea Fisheries Resources AgencyYoung IL Seo National Institute of Fisheries ScienceFALSEWe have been developing a state-space length-based assessment model, given that fish body size data were available instead of fish ages. With supported data from other divisions of NOAA, such as the Marine Debris Division, I created a project to quantify and diversify marine debris encountered in the Alaska commercial fishing fleet (pelagic and non-pelagic gear). The North Pacific Groundfish Observer Program has evolved over several decades into a complex system in which observers collect a multitude of data streams, including catch composition data. Observers utilize over 600 different codes for fish, birds, marine mammals, vertebrates and invertebrates in their catch composition reporting. This study focuses on a non-specific code of Miscellaneous. This code is currently used for a vast number of items that are not defined by other codes including the following: rocks, kelp, seaweed, wood, plastic, metal, fishing gear and trash. Many of these items naturally occur in the marine environment but some represent human-created garbage that is either accidentally or intentionally discarded into the sea. The intent of this study is to analyze specialized data collected by North Pacific Ground fish observers to quantify trash related items encountered in their normal randomized species composition samples. Observers were asked to separate any miscellaneous items encountered in their samples into two distinct groupings: naturally occurring items (rocks, kelp, seaweed, etc.) and man-made items (trash, plastic, rubber, etc.). Each distinct group of items were then counted and weighed. From the 21 datasets completed, 39.49% of encountered miscellaneous items were categorized as trash-related. The majority of these items were derelict fishing gear (twine, hooks, netting). With further analysis, the North Pacific Observer Program will create a new catch composition code that will account for trash-related items.","enrolled":false,"featured":false,"openForRegistration":true,"openForAttendeeHub@appFeature({\"feature\":\"displayInAttendeeHub\"})":null,"virtual":false,"included":false,"category":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionCategory:a119db44-d3c3-482e-a26e-7ffa3ac3b91f","typename":"SessionCategory"},"location":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionLocation:07bcd0d6-ded7-4edc-849a-9c6f0fd2de46","typename":"SessionLocation"},"webcast":null,"exhibitors":null,"__typename":"Session"},"Session:6afea232-c07c-4425-aa8b-e494fe22fc5b":{"id":"6afea232-c07c-4425-aa8b-e494fe22fc5b","name":"A timeline comparison of the invasion histories of bighead, silver, grass, and black carps in Nor","code":null,"start":"2021-11-06T05:00:00.000Z","end":"2021-11-11T04:00:00.000Z","description":"th America.Amy Benson USGS Wetlands and Aquatic Research CenterFALSEUsing a timeline format, we provide a comparative overview of the invasion histories of the four major Chinese aquaculture carps and human activities associated with those invasions, from the 1963 original importation of grass carp to present.  Responses to the invasion, including risk assessments, control efforts, and the development of the national management plan, are placed in context with the range and abundance of the carps, as determined by available records.   The invasion histories of the four species all vary substantially, largely in accordance with their use by humans.  Grass carp were and continue to be broadly stocked for vegetation control, resulting in their distribution across much of the United States.  Silver carp and bighead carp were introduced in the early 1970s.  Bighead carp were broadly used in aquaculture in the early 1980s, which corresponds to their rapid appearance across the midcontinent at that time.  Silver carp escaped almost immediately after importation but were never substantially used in aquaculture.  This resulted in a slower invasion at first than that of bighead carp, but silver carp are now far more abundant than bighead carp and have a similar range.  Black carp were the last to be successfully imported and most aquaculture use has relied on sterile triploids. Nevertheless, most black carp now captured are fertile diploids and apparently the product of wild reproduction, and their range and reported captures are currently increasing rapidly.","enrolled":false,"featured":false,"openForRegistration":true,"openForAttendeeHub@appFeature({\"feature\":\"displayInAttendeeHub\"})":null,"virtual":false,"included":false,"category":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionCategory:303ced98-8726-4db5-84c9-f2ba0175e276","typename":"SessionCategory"},"location":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionLocation:07bcd0d6-ded7-4edc-849a-9c6f0fd2de46","typename":"SessionLocation"},"webcast":null,"exhibitors":null,"__typename":"Session"},"Session:b93e945e-bcca-4c74-af03-ee08381218e7":{"id":"b93e945e-bcca-4c74-af03-ee08381218e7","name":"Accounting for a non-linear functional response when estimating prey dynamics using predator diet","code":null,"start":"2021-11-06T05:00:00.000Z","end":"2021-11-11T04:00:00.000Z","description":"dataMariano Koen-Alonso Fisheries and Oceans CanadaPaul Regular Fisheries and Oceans CanadaNoel Cadigan Memorial University of NewfoundlandFan Zhang Memorial University of NewfoundlandFALSEForage fish species are key in the transfer of energy from lower to upper trophic levels in marine ecosystems. Therefore, understanding their population dynamics, including population levels, is crucial for understanding productivity and the regulation of marine food webs. However, many forage fishes spend time in pelagic habitats and observations from bottom trawl surveys can produce poor estimates of their abundance. These estimates can be improved by using predator stomach contents as an additional sampling strategy, however non-linear relationships between prey abundance and predator consumption (i.e. the functional response) may bias these data as well. Using predator stomach contents and bottom trawl survey data, this study aimed to minimize this bias by developing a model to estimate prey dynamics and account for the predator functional response. This model was tested using a series of simulations and applied to a case-study of Northern sand lance (Ammodytes dubius) on the Grand Bank, Newfoundland, Canada. The simulations revealed that when predators consumed prey following a non-linear functional response, our model outperformed a classical model (the model adopted by most studies) that assumed a linear functional response. In the case study, we estimated the relative abundance of sand lance from 1995  2018, which exhibited oscillatory dynamics with a period of approximately seven years. Our results demonstrate that our model is capable of more accurately estimating the abundance of data-limited prey populations, which contributes to a better understanding of food web dynamics.","enrolled":false,"featured":false,"openForRegistration":true,"openForAttendeeHub@appFeature({\"feature\":\"displayInAttendeeHub\"})":null,"virtual":false,"included":false,"category":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionCategory:2f5a5028-7611-45b4-ab0a-ca83cc5641a8","typename":"SessionCategory"},"location":{"type":"id","generated":false,"id":"SessionLocation:07bcd0d6-ded7-4edc-849a-9c6f0fd2de46","typename":"SessionLocation"},"webcast":null,"exhibitors":null,"__typename":"Session"},"Session:25c37efe-b88c-40dc-a586-6213395a4556":{"id":"25c37efe-b88c-40dc-a586-6213395a4556","name":"AFS Issues and Actions around DEI","code":null,"start":"2021-11-06T05:00:00.000Z","end":"2021-11-11T04:00:00.000Z","description":"Chelsey Crandall FloridaCheryl Barnes NOAABeth Beard AFS HeadquartersAaron BunchSolomon David Nicholls State UniversityKatrina DunnGary Grossman U of GeorgiaLian Guo University of Massachusetts, Amherst; California Sea GrantAustin Happel Shedd AquariumMartha Mather Kansas State UCassidy Miles MissouriFrederick Nelson U California DavisSarah ONeal U WashingtonNivette Perez-Perez Inland BaysFALSEAs fisheries professionals we are charged with conserving and managing aquatic resources locally, nationally, and world-wide. These activities require and benefit from the inclusion of people from a diversity of identities, backgrounds, perspectives, and values. An inclusive culture within the fisheries profession empowers individuals to actively engage in processes that shape actions, policies, and cultures at all levels in the fisheries community. The goal of the Diversity, Equity, and Inclusion Standing Committee of the American Fisheries Society (AFS) is to identify systemic problems affecting diversity and inclusion in the Society and offer solutions for change. With AFS leadership, we hope to improve the culture of the Society by understanding and addressing barriers that have historically limited progress in achieving our shared vision of a more diverse and inclusive AFS. The AFS DEI standing committee was formed in 2020 after three years as a special committee. In our first year, we laid the groundwork for the committee and identified DEI issues, which led to multiple initiatives that we are considering with the help of the Equal Opportunities Section and leadership. Moving forward, we will implement action items for leadership (AFS, section, division), conference planners, and members to make AFS more diverse, equitable, and inclusive. For example, we suggest that planners black out all religious high holidays and not schedule meetings on those days. We also recommend that conference planners add pronouns to nametags to facilitate inclusive language related to all genders at meetings as well as help moderators use correct pronouns. We strive to serve all peoples of the fisheries community and to help AFS culture evolve to better serve this dynamic group of
